[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There\'s a fruit fly walking around right now that was never born. It is entirely simulated. Scientists took a real fly\'s brain, mapped every single neuron, dropped it in a body, and it just started walking around and behaving like'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a fly. No training data, no AI, just biology copied. And the company behind it says humans are next. So, this is Michael Andregg, and he\'s part of the'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'team that did it. So, we\'ve uploaded a fruit fly. We took the connectome of the fruit fly brain, applied a simple neuron model, and used it to control a physics-simulated body, closing the loop from neural activation to action. This'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fly, as he says, has a 91% behavior accuracy with only four things. One, the graph of the connections. Two, the weights as determined by the number'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of synapses connecting those neurons. Three, a map of excitatory and inhibitory neurons. And leaky integrate and fire. And if these sound confusing, let me break it down. So, the graph of'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'connections basically just means taking all the neurons and figuring out how they connect to each other. The weights is very similar to how a traditional large language model works. It is a way to basically predict behavior. The map'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of excitatory and inhibitory neurons basically means the neurons that say yes, go do that, or no, don\'t do that. Like, fire\'s hot, don\'t touch it. And food good, go get it. And the leaky'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'integrate and fire is just a rule set that determines how neurons will actually fire. Now, here\'s where it gets wild. He says, "Now, let\'s think about the fly. This is, in our view, a real,'

